# Planning Rules

## Mandatory skill — nawab-plans

**Whenever you are in Plan mode, drafting an implementation plan, or the task requires planning before coding**, you MUST:

1. Read and follow `.cursor/skills/nawab-plans/SKILL.md`
2. Use `.cursor/skills/nawab-plans/PLAN.template.md` as the plan structure
3. Consult `.cursor/skills/nawab-plans/SUBAGENT_ORCHESTRATION.md` when the plan involves subagents

This is compulsory — do not invent a thinner plan format. Scale depth with **project** vs **feature** mode; collapse unused sections as `N/A — [reason]` rather than skipping the skill.

Trivial one-line / typo fixes the user marked as skip-plan may skip a full nawab document — still do not invent an alternate planning skill.

## No Immediate Implementation

- Never begin implementation immediately.
- Never modify code before planning is completed.
- Never assume requirements are complete.

## Requirement Analysis

Before proposing implementation:

- Analyze the request.
- Identify objectives.
- Identify scope.
- Identify constraints.
- Identify dependencies.
- Identify risks.

## Clarification Requirements

- Never guess requirements.
- Never infer missing business logic.
- Never assume desired behavior.
- Never assume architecture.
- Never assume edge-case handling.

If any ambiguity exists:

- Stop.
- Ask clarifying questions.
- Wait for answers before planning.

## Implementation Plans

Every non-trivial task requires an implementation plan via **nawab-plans** (all required sections from the skill / template).

At minimum the plan must cover nawab sections for:

- Goal / north star & scope boundary
- Non-goals
- Prerequisites & blockers
- Dependencies / authority map
- Risks
- Deliverables
- Workstreams / phases
- Commit matrix & test gates
- Agent orchestration (when multi-agent)

Phase sizing still applies (small 2–3 · medium 3–5 · large 5–10), expressed inside the nawab phase structure.

## Approval Gate

After creating the implementation plan:

- Present the plan.
- Request approval.
- Do not begin implementation until approval is received.
